European inflation slipped into food
The accelerated inflation in the euro area is primarily due to the rapid rise in food prices.
Price increases in November were higher than expected in all 13 euro area countries, with annual inflation of 3.1% after 2.6% in October, the Luxembourg-based Statistical Office of the European Union announced.
Official forecasts only gave a 3 percent chance - Bloomberg reported.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the American, British and Canadian central banks, did not cut the basic interest rate on the pretext that the fall, together with rising commodity prices and reduced forced unemployment, would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "we have to negotiate" on inflation so that it does not have to intervene on this issue later.
Inflation in Germany, at 3.3%, broke the 12-year record; in Spain it rose from 3.6% to 4.1%.
Inflation soared in the euro area as a result of skyrocketing food and energy prices.
The rate of interest on wheat rose by 88%, and the rate on soybeans reached its highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more was paid for vegetable oil and dairy products in 2007.
The price of crude oil on the world market rose this year by 52 percent, reaching almost $100 a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from the current 2.1% in 2008 to 2.5% in 2009, but will decline to 1.9% by 2009.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain at around 3 percent over the next 3 or 4 months, but the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to cut interest rates twice during 2008.
Gallup predicts a government crisis
After a long stalemate, by early December support for the Alliance of Young Democrats had risen significantly, reaching its highest level since 2002, while Gallup had never before experienced such a low level - 13 percent - for the Socialists.
The difference in the case of the party's confident voters - due to the greater firmness of the opposition voters - would mean support of more than two thirds (71%) versus support of a fifth for the Socialists (20%).
According to the poll, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not even reach the necessary limit to have any parliamentary seats: their support among the entire population is two percent.
Among the confident voters there is one percent more sympathizers on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous low point - it has never been higher, 41 percent the proportion of those who judged the economic situation of the country especially bad, while another 46 percent believe that the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the more hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about the change in their own economic situation.
As for the coming year, the majority of the population expects the situation to deteriorate and only one tenth expect an improvement.
In December, 71 per cent of those questioned, the highest figure in any previous Gallup survey, felt that the Prime Minister was performing poorly rather than well.
13 percent of those questioned trust or have a high level of trust in Ferenc Gyurcsány, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of those questioned.
54% of the population have no confidence in the Prime Minister and 27% do not trust the President of the Alliance of Young Democrats.
One of the indicators of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks it is possible to control the discontent experienced in the face of the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the October riots last year 35 per cent felt it would be desirable to keep the Government and the Prime Minister in power, this proportion is now only 20 per cent, while the relative majority (33 per cent) believe that the only solution is to hold new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterised by the fact that 60 per cent of those questioned about participation said they would certainly participate and another 20 per cent said they were likely to participate.
In comparison, in "a general election to be held this Sunday" only 55 percent of the population would be certain to participate and another 15 percent believe their participation likely.
74 percent of the population would disapprove of the payment of tuition fees, 79 percent of the payment of medical consultations and 84 percent of the payment of hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of the voters would reject the introduction of tuition fees, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, Tesco has quintupled its prices
The average price increase of 16 per cent was maintained by the hypermarkets in the Budaörs gold trading triangle, with the difference that VAT was not increased this year.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year, the average price of the Napi newspaper's Christmas basket rose by 16 percent in the Budaörs gold trading triangle, but all hypermarkets saw growth well above HUF 1,000.
As in December last year the prices in food supermarkets had already "raised", there was no drastic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they could buy last year for well under 9 000 HUF, they cannot buy today for even 10 000.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF by a minimum of 91 HUF.
And the highest basket value was 10,573 HUF.
(in 2003 that basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a sharp increase in the price of turkey breast fillet, nutmeg and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data from the Central Statistics Office, although in the Auchan we also found a kilo of bread at the price of 139 HUF.
Competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than HUF 200.
It was also surprising in this shop that the price of Coca-Cola in a two-litre redeemable bottle was less than HUF 200, so that this product, even at the price of the bottle, cost only HUF 257.
But in Napi Auchan's basket, it was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, with respect to last year's Christmas prices, Cora increased by 15%, while Tesco and Auchan by about 18% the prices listed in Napi's basket.
Comparing the values of last year's most expensive basket with this year's cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between last year's cheapest and this year's most expensive has been 21 percent.
The average growth was HUF 1480.
Last year the average price increase was HUF 1206, so that during last year's Christmas the VAT increase was felt in prices.
It was this process that destroyed trade, supermarkets were visibly unable to decide on the price range to be applied to each product and to calculate the effect of price change on consumption.
(If the trader plans the speed of a product's circulation poorly, he may lose a significant profit on the margin that is adjusted to the sales volume.)
The price increase of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the VAT increase that the most expensive basket was HUF 1720 higher than the value recorded in 2006, while the difference in the cheapest basket was only HUF 844.
This year there were no such extremes, since the highest price now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased by 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, a catastrophic price increase was recorded in less than 20 months, with hypermarkets seeing more than a 30 percent increase in the price of basic consumer goods.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Statistical Office: for some basic foodstuffs, the latter recorded a price increase of more than 30 per cent over the 12 months.
So, for example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of eggs.)
According to the Napi basket, in this latter case this seems almost impossible, because the price of this product, which was quite expensive last year compared to the base, recorded, in the worst case, barely a 10 percent increase in prices.
According to all the indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, and can force price increases on even multinationals.
Hypermarkets don't complain about the golden triangle of commerce, they constantly talk about positive results.
In our experience, most of the consumers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
They buy large quantities of all the produce, taking the preserved food with them by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, large queues formed in all three stores in front of the boxes because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that in the interior of the country sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to the survey institutes because revenues are below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in that of appliances.
Many hospitals save money on disinfectants
This year several thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals, primarily due to the improper use of antibiotics.
The hygiene conditions prevailing in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds and the overload of staff do not favour the control of infections - says the chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many hospitals, even disinfectants are economical.
Recently, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
A man hospitalized after a serious accident was found to have the antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred at this same hospital earlier this year.
A person injured in a serious car accident was discharged from hospital and the same patient had to return to hospital shortly afterwards as a result of MRSA infection and since then no major surgical intervention has been possible due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10, 1094 cases of hospital infection by multiresistant agents have been registered in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System - said Karolina Böröcz, chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Center.
This means that hospitals have certainly recorded this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents, the rest is unknown.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i. e. methicillin-oxacillin resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
One third of humans carry the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) respond well to antibiotics and are easily treated.
However, once antibiotics are over- or unduly applied, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics become highly antibiotic-resistant and quickly become contagious in inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, e.g. wound infections or sepsis, first to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with weakened organism, to the elderly or to people with low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the János Hospital there is nothing special about the MRSA infection, these infections are everyday in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
"These patients are isolated, the nursing staff attends them in rubber gloves and mask and there are adequate antibiotics for their treatment" - said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients in hospital are examined for MRSA in advance, but even this cannot prevent infection in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples.
In most cases, it would be possible to prevent hospital MRSA infections, but the current national hospital circumstances are not conducive to preventing the formation and infection of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine inpatients and immediately isolate patients who carry MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not a trend in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also because the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most cases come to light when MRSA infections are visible in the patient - said the chief medical officer of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict guidelines for the use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives for the treatment of infections and diseases.
The aim is to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, that is, that microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less frequent in the case of ambulant patients or in basic care - said Karolina Böröcz.
You save money with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is transmitted from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Handwashing, the use of rubber gloves and masks are therefore very important, but there are also considerable shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent epidemics, patients should be separated by at least 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, it can also be experienced - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals with less favourable economic situation, disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a higher probability of infection.
Karolina Böröcz believes that where adequate prevention measures are in place, fewer such infections are recorded or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Governmental programme against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so in every country it is fought.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
The programme appears to be successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections are showing a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has as one of its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
Negative alcohol control of the police commander who caused a fatal accident
The official expert report has been made on the case of the fatal accident caused by the police commander of the XXII district.
The possibility of the drunk driving or in a state of stupor of the then-resigned commander of the police of the XXII district, who on Tuesday hit and killed a passenger, can be excluded - said Attila Morvai, spokesman of the General Prosecutor's Office of the Capital, after having prepared the expert report on the case.
The expert report confirmed the result of the primary alcohol check which had already found that the former police commander did not consume any alcoholic beverages before getting behind the wheel.
The then-head of the police station of the XXII district, on Tuesday with his private vehicle when turning to the street Kossuth Lajos of the XXII district ran over a man of 55 years, who intended to cross the street, but not in the designated area for pedestrians.
(This latter fact, i.e. that the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the road, according to the regulations of the Traffic Code are not mitigating circumstances, the driver must always give way when bending.)
The passerby lost his life after being hospitalized.
The district police chief resigned and requested his retirement, according to the police statement, because he was deeply moved by the case.
The investigation of the case is in charge of the Budapest Investigative Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also said that the former police commander from the beginning cooperated with the prosecutors in charge of the investigation.
EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and the Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three credit-limit agreements worth a total of EUR 400 million in Budapest on Friday to finance infrastructure for education, transport and the environment, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance transport and environmental protection projects from the Hungarian budget, which will be carried out from the Cohesion Fund grant, of which the parties had previously signed a loan agreement worth EUR 100 million, the contract they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million loan agreement is also intended to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for this objective in Hungary. The decision on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be taken later, when the loan agreement is extended.
The parties signed a contract for €50 million for innovations, which the budget will use mainly for the innovation and research project at the University of Debrecen.
The talks also covered the construction of the 4th Metro line.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary finalised the details of the financing of the Metro with the EU, they would re-examine whether or not it was necessary to modify the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this could take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest on loans is adjusted to EURIBOR and the EIB offers an eight-year grace period, without charging a commission for keeping the loan available to the debtor.
Bulgaria, the real estate haven of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is admirable - the attention of the whole of Europe is directed towards this Balkan country, which was mentioned a little earlier.
What, where and who are buying in the even cheaper EU market, which will be getting more expensive quickly?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The preferred target for real estate purchases in Eastern Europe is undoubtedly Bulgaria, with its cheap ski-track apartments and beach villas.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while on the Albena beaches, the "Golden Coast", the "Sun Coast", the old Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are also looking for real estate in the surroundings of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, sooner or later the central part of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will also attract real estate developers and more and more people will buy property in the especially cheap part of Rus.
The capital Sofia will also be attractive, with commercial and office spaces promising a rapid recovery of investment.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of the most attractive golfing destinations in Europe, being a prime destination during the other two seasons as well as summer and winter.
Therefore, cautious investors are already making their purchases, for example in the vicinity of Bansko.
Analysts say that those who buy property in Bulgaria are also trying to change their lives and lifestyles.
Most of the customers are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot promoters are also present and there are traditionally many Russian customers on the Black Sea beaches and in ski resorts.
Foreign customers can be classified into three groups - says Georgi Jankov, Re/Max regional director in Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle here buy new or renovated properties for a price between 50 and 100 thousand euros or old houses in poor condition between 5 and 15 thousand euros, to renovate them later.
They require good communication and access, and they also want to be close to a big city, shops and usually a local doctor.
The second category is comprised of chalet buyers (Bulgaria was in the top 10 holiday destinations for Germans in December).
The third group is made up of real estate investors who make purchases in the hope of benefiting in the medium or long term.
The price of capital property is constantly rising, as demand is increasing.
Although Bulgaria has the lowest property prices in the European Union, over the last five years they have increased by 21 per cent annually.
The increase in real estate prices considerably exceeds the growth in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarians
According to Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, the meetings at the level of experts will end on Tuesday and on Wednesday after the official inauguration, the negotiations at the level of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap for efforts after the Kyoto Protocol emissions reduction period, which runs until 2012.
There are lively discussions on the particular between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that it does not wish to negotiate on precise figures, although it is likely to agree that, compared with 1990, emissions of greenhouse gases will decrease by 25 to 40 percent by 2020.
Another major issue of the conference is whether or not the industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological aid to countries in need.
An agreement was also reached on aid to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be managed by a 16-member board of directors, probably within the UN Global Environment Fund (GEF).
The six per cent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister for Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement by 2009.
The minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 from 1990 levels, whether or not the "post-2012 agreement" is signed, and is willing to commit to reducing even by 30% if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in accordance with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries signatory to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to a 5.2 per cent reduction, within which the then 15 EU Member States committed to an 8 per cent reduction.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent over the period 1985-87, which Hungary will meet - says the press release from the Ministry of Environment.
The international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed in two years' time, because if it is not, its entry into force will be postponed until after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments assumed in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international system for reducing emissions, the need for which was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the international scientific association of the UN that deals with climate change, which won the Nobel Peace Prize.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and an increase of more than 2°C in the average temperature of the earth could not be prevented, which according to scientists would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
The British Army recruits on YouTube
British Army units on a video distribution site post footage of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First, the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube services: Special Forces deployed in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos of their actions against the Taliban - BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled at the General Operations Corps in Kandahar, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
Already 139 recordings from air force soldiers have been uploaded to the Internet and their "channel" has been viewed by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered in the spring of 2007 under the name "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions in Iraq and Afghanistan, while both the British Commonwealth Office and the Multinational Forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos for recruitment purposes, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to present the public with the true purpose of the British military presence abroad.
This type of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to conventional television recruitment spots - defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC - but inevitably has some political message, since it justifies the rationale for military actions decided by the government in a specific way.
The Americans have prepared a video game
The army is also concerned that, in addition to the recordings that have been circumspectly edited and censored, the distributor also features amateur videos, for example about the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, the officers talk about losses, without presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, numerous videos of actual operations have been uploaded from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British Army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
The Americans use a slightly different way for recruitment with the free downloadable shooting video games called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers.
