The forces of the giant strike are gathering
The League Unions and the National Federation of Workers' Commissions will form a strike commission on Friday to coordinate the strike on Monday that will last indefinitely.
On Saturday a protest rally will be held, while on Monday - the day of the final vote on the public health law - the strike will begin.
This action will certainly cause great difficulties in transport, as rail traffic will be completely stopped and until 1 p.m. the workers of the Budapest Public Transport Company will also be on strike.
On Friday afternoon, the League Unions will report on the details of their Monday strike, which they will hold together with the National Federation of Workers' Commissions.
The strike committee of the LIGA and the National Union of Machinists will also be formed to coordinate the actions on Monday.
On Saturday a protest rally will be held, while on Monday the participating unions will go on strike for an indefinite period, if no agreement is reached with the government.
This means that - on the day of the parliamentary vote on the public health law - they did not inform about the date of the end of the strike started.
If the National Assembly disapproves of the public health law, the unions will immediately withdraw their call for strike action.
Instead, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide on the future.
On the basis of the Monday agenda of the National Assembly it is also possible that the public health law will only be voted on in the late hours of the night, or at best close to midnight.
The strike on Monday will lead to significant difficulties in transport: the railways will be closed indefinitely, part of Budapest's public transport may be shut down in the morning and more than half of Volán's buses will be shut down.
At the same time, in many parts of the country, half of the roads will be closed.
Numerous unions and civil organizations have joined the strike, their names are constantly updated on the League's Web page.
Some unions announced their strike for an indefinite period, others for a definite period.
Until Thursday afternoon, the State Railroad and the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers (SLTF) could not reach an agreement even on minimum services, although as the Christmas holidays approach, more and more people travel on trains.
According to information received so far, from the beginning of the day until 13 hours will be on strike the workers of the Collective Transport Company of Budapest, the Airports of Budapest from 7 to 9 in the morning, will hold a strike of four hours the Unions of LIGA of the Electrical Industry and of Thermal Energy, the Unions of the Educators called a strike of 2 and the Democratic Syndicate of the Educators from 2 to 8 hours.
The Hungarian Medical Association will go on a national strike at alternate times and the Democratic Union of Health and Social Sector Workers (SDTSSS) which are part of the Trade Union Cooperation Forum, will hold a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands made by the League is that the government withdraw its proposal for public health reform and submit a new conception to a social debate.
The second demand is that the new way of calculating pensions should be introduced gradually, which will come into force next year.
The third is to ensure, even before 2010, that in the case of advanced pensions, the occupations which deserve it can enter the system.
The fourth reason for the strike is that the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers (SLTF) which is part of the League Unions, do not accept the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport on the railway sidelines and are waiting for another proposal.
Political Capital[b1]: The Hungarian Guard increases the risk in the country
According to the Risk Analysing Division of Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, which was set up in August this year with the support of the Movement for a Better Hungary, has in various ways increased the political risk to Hungary and the region.
The company's "risk warning" states that the greatest political risk in relation to the Hungarian Guard's activity is the fact that "with the worsening of ethnic tensions between the Roma and non-Gypsy population of Hungary, even in the short term, violent ethnic clashes may occur".
The main reason for this is that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy is probably to provoke an event of this nature - added the representative of the research institute.
They said that this was one of the main faults of the Hungarian political leaders: "the public leaders gave up the public debate on the Roma problem to the representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who were able to base their political strategy on the discrepancies between Roma and Hungarians".
This aggravates the problem, impedes normal dialogue, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts, they estimate.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activity of the National Guard, as a result of the great attention of the national and international media, "significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, especially as regards the stability and democratic development of the country".
They remind us that: from the autumn of 2006 the reorganisation of the radical and extreme right groups in Hungary received increasing publicity and momentum and that since the summer of 2007 numerous organisations have been formed in the country which define themselves as "national self-defense associations".
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civilian organizations, while they openly proclaim the training of their members for defense - even armed - (civil defense, national defense, defense of public order), alluding to the ineptitudes of the police, the army, that is, the State" - they add.
They said: all this is done in accordance with the method which tries to give a civil presentation to different political aspirations, based on the dissatisfaction of society with politics and political parties.
The Commission has also been asked to draw up a list of the Member States which have not yet ratified the Convention.
The analysis shows that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is also a risk factor from the point of view of neighbourly relations.
"In recent months, in many neighboring states, the Hungarian Guard has been referred to as a potential danger, while ultra-nationalist political figures in certain neighboring countries want to justify their own anti-Hungarian policy with the creation of the Hungarian Guard.
All this affects the political stability of the region" - they added.
According to the research institute, the creation of the Hungarian Guard is not an isolated phenomenon in Central and Eastern Europe, so that political risks have increased throughout the region.
They wrote that the Hungarian Guard functions similarly to, for example, the Bulgarian National Guard, whose constitution was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (UNB).
The formation of the Bulgarian Guard is due to the mass riots of the Gypsies that occurred in one of the neighborhoods of Sofia (Krasna Poliana).
