The party isn't always written in red numbers.
In Hungary, the law defines precisely the days that are written in red numbers in the calendar and it has already become a widespread practice that around the holidays - which next year will be less - the working days are reorganized.
Even in the EU or North America, the holidays are not uniform.
Hungarian laws distinguish between national holidays, state holidays and public holidays.
The holiday period is mainly associated with religious and historical holidays.
We celebrate the New Year too: both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are festive - the latter especially so that those who spent time celebrating the old year can rest.
Throughout the year we have eleven holidays written with red numbers on the calendar.
It is a national holiday on March 15 in memory of the 1848 revolution and on October 23, commemorative day of the 1956 revolution.
On August 20 we celebrate the founding of the State, on May 1st the holiday of work, on November 1st and 2nd we remember our relatives and friends who died.
In addition, in our country there are two days of Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with a weekend, so often a bridge is made when there is only one working day before or after the holiday.
In exchange for the longer weekends, you cannot miss work or school on the Saturdays before.
It is the Minister of Labour who regulates in his specific decree when it is necessary to work exactly in exchange for the day immediately before or after the holiday.
This legal rule is binding on all employers and their employees, as well as on employees and civil servants.
However, it is not compulsory for enterprises and service institutions which, because of their function, work uninterruptedly even during public holidays.
This year the work order can only be altered around the end of the year holidays: from 24 December onwards, life in the country is practically stopped, since according to experience, most people "bridge" during the days between Christmas and the end of the year or take their holidays during these days.
Next year several of our holidays will coincide with mid-week or weekend, so there will be fewer changes in working days than this year.
First, the agenda will be changed around the Labour Day so that workers can rest for four consecutive days.
Saturday, April 26 will be a working day, so that Friday, May 2 will be a holiday.
The other change relates to the 23 October holiday: on Saturday 18 October, instead of Friday 24, you will have to work.
However, next year during the New Year's holiday, you can rest, since from December 24 onwards you will not work in almost any place, even if the last day of the year is a Wednesday.
Six little deterrents to make your colleagues' lives bitter
E-mails we forget to send, text messages we never receive, innocent lies we pass on without realizing it: they are all part of our daily workplace folklore.
You have to decide whether you will adapt to the little annoyances or consciously avoid the confusing situations that may irritate others.
