Banks want to solve the crisis
The Federal Reserve Bank of the United States, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian central banks decided to fight together against the financial market crisis.
The monetary market will receive more than 100 billion dollars through tenders.
In these auctions the banks auction off the interest rates at which they are able to lend money.
For example, the American Fed will send out a bid of 40 billion dollars, and then another 24 billion dollars will be provided by the European and Swiss central banks.
After the September 11 attacks, it is the first time that central banks from different states have agreed on this coordinated process to protect and mitigate the consequences of the financial crisis.
"This step should solve the biggest economic problem, namely the continuing growth of the scarcity of free capital that banks could lend", wrote Bernard Baumohl of the consultancy firm Economic Outlook Group in his report for clients.
"This coordinated action by central banks probably reduced the recession in the United States from 65 percent to 50 percent", Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already spent sixty billion dollars on unpaid loans, mostly in the United States.
Economists still expect billions in losses.
"Central banks must be really afraid of what is still ahead when they decided to take this step", said ABN Amro's chief economist, Kieran Davies.
"It seems that the situation is really bad", he added.
Central banks fear that they will have the same problems with access to loans and that they will therefore have to lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the American economy into recession with different impacts on the growth of the world economy.
The central banks thus decided, after failing to reduce the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate used for lending money on the interbank market.
This means that banks were constantly afraid to borrow money even when the central banks of the US, Canada and Britain cut their interest rates several times during the autumn.
"It will have the same effect as another fall in interest rates", Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some economists are not surprised that the step taken by the central banks contributes to igniting the crisis because it does not solve the fundamental problem of the collapse of the housing market in the USA.
