A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are freely available.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of shelves in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not available until now only for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. individually and nominally, at the request of a former victim or his right holders.
The 11 states that administer them - Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
Since the ratification process of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening is effective from yesterday.
The Commission shall be empowered to adopt delegated acts in accordance with Article 21 of this Regulation.
Historians' access to Bad Arolsen will allow them to search "particularly for the movements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health status of forced labourers", explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives run by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, such as Germany, opposed the opening of these nomination documents to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
So is the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of certain deportation victims.
The records of concentration camps or of Gestapo arrest warrants had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find the peasants who had been deported or subjected to forced labour and, eventually, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, over 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen are processing tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest to a part of the scientific community.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents", Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Research Center on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität in Berlin, had stated in 2006.
