Congress approves the transposition of Mifid, which entered into force on 1 November
In parallel with its parliamentary procedure, which ended today with the vote by the Congress of the amendments incorporated into the draft in the Senate, the Government has submitted to public hearing the regulation that will develop the new law, with the aim of both entering into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the various groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by Members and Senators to negotiate and agree on the best rules to ensure investor protection and to regulate in detail the activity of institutions so that markets can function efficiently.
The Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, modernises financial markets, strengthens investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (NSMC) and encourages cooperation between the various supervisors in the European Union.
The new rules will allow the provision of financial advisory services to both specialist firms and natural or legal persons and create a new type of financial services firm (FSA), financial advisory firms (FAs), which join securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
It also expands the number of systems for the execution of transactions in financial instruments, so that regulated secondary markets are joined by multilateral trading systems and order internalisation systems, which will compete with current exchange operators.
The Law also requires investment firms to disclose information on the market about key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management practices and requires them to keep a record of all transactions they carry out, to facilitate supervision by the CNMV.
In its passage through the Congressional Economic Committee, several amendments were incorporated, among which it is noted that securitised debt is considered a "complex" financial instrument given its high risk to the investor, as has been demonstrated by the case of US subprime mortgage debt.
The transposition of the directive also took advantage of the legal limitations on the roles of graduates in economics and business 30 years after the Royal Decree of 1977 which defined the professional roles of economists.
The Senate also introduced new figures in the financial sector, such as the mediator, who will work as an outsourced agent, will not require the CNMV's authorization and will be able to provide its services of marketing products and attracting clients to different investment companies at the same time.
