What insurance is good for me?
Car insurance, which covers the driver in the event of a potential accident, is a major expense, depending on a number of factors, such as age, sex, age of the licence, marital status, type of vehicle to be insured or use of the vehicle, among others.
Having the car is just the beginning.
And the fact is, choosing the right car insurance is even harder than choosing the model of vehicle.
First of all, we have to be clear about what we're talking about.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insured.
This commitment is embodied in an insurance contract, which provides that the company receives the value of the agreed premium in exchange for being held liable for the obligation to pay compensation in the event of a loss.
The premium is the price of the insurance, which is determined by taking into account various factors, such as age, sex, age of the licence, marital status, type of vehicle to be insured or the use of the vehicle, among others.
Insurance companies set their prices based on statistics, so the higher the chance of an accident, the higher the premium.
That is why both over 25s and women have to pay lower premiums, as statistics show that they have a lower accident rate because of their prudence.
Also, based on the count, the companies have concluded that married people tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use of the vehicle will influence the frequency, and thus the likelihood of having some kind of accident.
Increasing the frequency increases the probability.
There are many variables that insurance companies take into account when setting the premium price.
This is why the driver must study the situation carefully to choose the car insurance that best suits his profile.
Here we will explain the most important variables when choosing one or another type of insurance, so that this, in addition to adapting to the characteristics of the insured, offers a reasonable price.
Young people under 25 face a number of disadvantages in purchasing affordable insurance, such as lack of driving experience and the age of the licence.
Although the ideal way to be well insured is all-hazard insurance, there are other cheaper options.
The most cautious drivers can opt for a full risk with deductible, so that they get the coverage of an all-risk insurance but at a more affordable price.
This type of agreement would mean that the customer would pay a part of the amount of the claim.
"The part of the amount of the claim that the customer contributes will be pre-established according to the value of the premium, which will be higher the lower the amount", specifies Luis Noguera, chief executive in Spain of First Europa, an online insurance mediator.
Another option is extended third party insurance, whereby the customer is protected against damage to third parties, but not against damage to his own car.
Plus, it would be covered for theft, arson and vehicle loss.
A word of advice.
If you are under 25, try to be careful and avoid accidents as much as possible, as this will affect the bonus and may reduce the cost of insurance in the future.
A bonus is a reduction on the basic rate that the company owns.
On the contrary, a penalty is a surcharge on that basic tariff.
'Bonuses and penalties will depend on the company and its profit.
If the company has had a good year, it can afford to increase the bonuses", Noguera explains.
After the age of 25, drivers find it easier to take out insurance, since the accident rate is reduced by the experience gained.
For this reason, it is best to hire a franchise-based all-risk.
"Young people are usually unable to make use of the experience they have acquired in an accident, or even in driving", says the Spanish director of the European company, adding that most accidents occur in the second year of driving, once the 'newbie's fear' has passed.
However, if the client is married but has no children, it is preferable that he negotiate full-risk insurance, as long as his financial situation permits it, of course.
On the other hand, children are considered by the insurers as the least likely to be injured, so the surcharges will be lower.
In this case, the best insurance would be all-risk insurance with deductible (which can be 300 euros) or, where a high level of bonus is available, third party insurance extended from the third year of the vehicle's life.
"They are more relaxed and have a greater purchasing power to afford the luxury of taking on a larger amount of franchise", said Luis Noguera.
For pensioners, it is advisable to take out deductible all-risk insurance (€150), or extended third-party insurance if you have a high level of bonus.
Car insurance is important, not only because it covers the driver against possible accidents, but also because it represents a significant expense, which is why it is essential to study properly the insurance that best suits us according to our personal situation.
