Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises the price of gas, Russia will have to pay higher transit fees.
An earlier dispute last year reduced supplies to EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow came with the Ukrainian government and the Russian state, gas monopoly owner Gazprom, trying to agree on the amount of money Ukraine was to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom stated that it would charge Ukraine more, as Ukraine has committed to pay an extra 50% in 2008 for gas coming from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say it could be that Ukraine pays 40% more for Gazprom imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important transit routes for gas during the talks", Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters news agency.
"Changes in gas prices should not be related to our arguments about the levels of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine".
The last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom cut off supply to Ukraine in January 2006.
This meant a drop in exports to Western Europe, which quickly drove up prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the EU's supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it is not yet fully developed.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own gas supplies from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian nations.
NHS "should test foreign workers"
The Scottish NHS needs to check the criminal record records of employees from outside Europe, a watchdog said.
The recommendation by the Auditor General Robert Black came after it was found that a foreign doctor was linked to the Glasgow airport attack in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish NHS has no exact idea of how many foreign staff it has.
However, their report pointed out other checks that are being carried out correctly through a sample of five health authorities.
The Auditor General checked the number of foreign staff recruited outside the European Economic Area in the wake of the Glasgow airport attacks.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at Paisley's Royal Alexandra Hospital, was arrested at the airport after crashing a jeep into the doors of the airport terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who performed at the Old Bailey by video conference in October, charged in connection with the alleged car bombings in the UK.
NHS hopes to carry out pre-employment checks on candidates to ensure they meet the qualifications, experience and authorisation to work in the UK.
Although the Scottish Health Board uses "Disclosure Scotland" to carry out criminal background checks, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain this information outside of Britain.
The Auditor General's report recommends, among other measures, that boards should have guidance from the Criminal Records Bureau, which helps employers with criminal controls in many countries outside Britain.
"Although we found some of the personal records with evidence of these checks, this is not a routine review", the report says.
Black states that the Scottish NHS has a high level of compliance with its own employment policies, but notes that: 'our report highlights areas where improvements can be made to ensure that the necessary information is available on the number of overseas staff in the NHS'.
BMA Scotland president Dr Peter Terry said it was "very unlikely" that pre-employment checks could identify potential NHS employees who might commit terrorist acts in the future.
"The report suggests that pre-employment checks work in NHS Scotland but it is not clear what the added value of the recommendations made is", he explained.
The Scottish health authorities state that they currently have 1,161 foreigners, most of them doctors and nurses
But the auditor general warned that the number may be higher, in part because boards have trouble identifying which employees have indefinite residency permits.
The investigation also found that the verification procedures set out by the NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian were being broadly complied with.
This includes passport checks, work permits and qualification checks.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing the policy and guidance for foreigners' pre-employment in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon says: "I had a great interest in this work being carried out in the wake of the Glasgow airport terrorist attack.
He added that the Scottish government, in conjunction with health boards, could consider the recommendations in the reports and that this would be reflected in the updating of pre-employment control guidelines for all work groups - including foreigners - which they planned to publish next month.
