Venus' climate may give a glimpse of Earth's future
Venus may once have been a suitable place for life, scientists declared yesterday.
Data from an orbiting European spacecraft showed the planet more like a twin of Earth than had been observed previously.
Venus is the closest planet to Earth.
The two planets are similar in size and orbit, although Venus is slightly closer to the sun.
Millions of years ago, Venus may have had conditions similar to those that made Earth a habitable planet, scientists now believe.
But the effects of carbon dioxide and the greenhouse effect, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation and slower solar rotation sent Venus into a very different kind of development.
Today the planet has no water, the surface temperature is high enough to melt lead, and it is eroded by hurricane winds and lightning storms.
The results of the European Space Agency's Venus Express, which has been studying the planet for a year, offer a picture of how the Earth could develop catastrophic changes because of climate.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at Oxford University and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, states: "It is becoming clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, when they are two planets so similar.
"Our new data make it possible to construct a scenario where Venus began as Earth, possibly with a habitable environment millions of years ago".
