Card sharks
Is the subprime mortgage crisis infecting the American credit card market?
When there's blood in the water, it's natural for some dorsal fins to swim around excitedly.
Today, with the American housing market in crisis, predators have their eyes on the country's credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs estimate that credit card losses could reach $99 million if the subprime mortgage crisis spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of infection are already showing.
There is an increase in both card charges and crime rates, which measures the proportion of balances that have not been redeemed or are more than 30 days late respectively.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken a $1.4 million charge on its American consumer finance business, in part due to the weakness of card borrowers.
However, it's too early to panic.
Delinquency and crime are at low levels.
According to Moody's, a rating agency, the third-quarter crime rate of 3.89% was almost one percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be partly explained by technical factors.
A change in the American Bankruptcy Law of Persons (2005) resulted in a sharp drop in bankruptcy filings, which in turn represented a large loss on credit cards; the number of applications (and therefore, of default) would be growing again, or it may happen that conditions for borrowers were getting worse.
The industry also reports solid repayment rates, which show how much of its debts consumers pay each month.
And confidence in credit cards and asset-backed securities is pretty solid, despite the paralysis in other financial areas.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicts that emissions volumes for 2007 will be about 25% higher than last year.
Direct channels of infection from the crisis between subprime mortgages and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers like to charge credit card debts now that credit institutions are expiring.
But credit card issuers look more to the flow of cash than to assets, so falling prices do not necessarily trigger a change in borrowers' creditworthiness.
They may even work to out-run the broadcasters.
The incentives for consumers to continue to repay the mortgage decreases if the properties are worth less than the value of the loan; and as a result, paying off the card debt rises to the top of the priority list.
Card issuers can also respond quickly and flexibly to the difficult conditions that mortgage lenders encounter by changing interest rates or altering creditors' balances.
That should in theory reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of assets.
"We're not going to wake up one day and reevaluate all the loans", says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
If a sudden subprime infection in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained decline are much more real.
If house prices are lower and a credit crunch pushes America into recession, the industry undoubtedly faces a harsher future.
We need to keep an eye on those dorsal fins.
