Venus: twin brother of Earth.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that had not been considered until now. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered lightning in the atmosphere and swirls at the poles, the same that appear also in winter on Earth.
For three decades researchers had suspected that lightning might exist on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it has discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere, where lightning strikes from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the scientific journal Nature.
According to the famous Urey-Miller model of the origin of life, lightning caused life on Earth: storms could have triggered reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
On Venus, it is not: if life ever existed there, it would have to be in one of the earliest stages of evolution", explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
Today, life cannot exist on the surface of Venus. The atmospheric pressure is nearly 100 times greater than on Earth, and the surface is 500°C hot, so low that temperatures below zero can be reached.
"Venus is possibly a 'diabolical' twin of Earth, but it's still a twin", Russell said.
The main objective of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth in mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research of this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for the research of Venus.
The latest research results, which will be featured in many articles in Nature, according to the researchers, underscore not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also shows that the neighboring planets have more in common with Earth than we had assumed", reports ESA.
Despite the already known stormy winds at the North Pole, researchers also discovered a vortex of clouds in the south polar region that rotates faster.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the upper atmospheric layers of the Earth's poles, as described by a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute for Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the solar system is almost as massive as the earth, and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers, it is almost as large.
This planet also called the morning star or evening star orbits the sun for almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus is equal to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus, with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars, does not bear much resemblance to Earth, scientists assume that both planets were formed under the same conditions.
On both planets, water had clumped together, which on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus it dissociated into the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had been converted into carbon rocks, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
