If you associate the terms Sweden and wooden box, you think of Ikea, but you don't think of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At present, wooden boxes produced in Sweden are like the shadow that weighs on Warhol's list of works.
Most of the 94 "type" Brillo-Boxes on this list are fake.
After the Swedish newspaper Expressen raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes, the Moderna Museet in Stockholm conducted internal research and came to disappointing conclusions: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former director of the museum Pontus Hultén gave to the Moderna Museet, are fake, and nearly a hundred of the other "Stockholm-type" ones, which are in circulation on the international art market, are also.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confused relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painting the wooden boxes red, blue and white, with the same pattern as they had on the "Brillo" soap powder cartons.
According to Warhol, the exhibition of his works in 1968 at the Moderna Museet exhibited hundreds of Brillo-cardboard boxes. These were not made by Warhol (due to expenses), but were brought directly from the "Brillo" cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but specimens (which were only objects) on display.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol allowed the production of Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, but they were not exhibited in the Modern Museet museum.
Witnesses of those times now speak of almost fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auctions as originals of the "Stockholm-type" "Brillo-Boxes" authorized by Andy Warhol.
At auctions, some of them were bought for over $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous director of the Pontus Hultén museum made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden almost a hundred of the wooden boxes that Warhol left were produced and exhibited, he was left with them.
But in fact, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malmö for Hultén and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, the head of the conservators at the Moderna Museet, investigated six Brillo-Boxes owned by the museum and also three privately owned Swedish ones that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm.
On the contrary, the structure of the 1990 copies shows that the paint was applied with a roller without directly printing the pressed plates.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes", says Lars Nittve, the director of the Moderna Museet museum and adds that if the "Andy Warhol Art" Authentication Commission in New York does not reach any conclusion, the Moderna Museet museum will classify these six boxes as copies/exhibits".
Already in July the Authentication Commission formally announced that it accepts these "grave accusations" that they are boxes of soap powder.
But from that moment on everything there remained in absolute silence.
